# Intuition
The things you need to keep in mind:
- The path will be a valid Unix command. Yes you read that right. Unix path command.
- Entering "../" will change the current directory to it's parent directory.
- Entering "./" will stay in the same current directory.
- Entering "x" will visit the child directory named **x**.

Now for the output your result must ensure the following things:
- The path starts with a single slash '/'.
- Any two directories are separated by a single slash '/'.
- The path does not end with a trailing '/'.
- The path only contains the directories on the path from the root directory to the target file or directory (i.e., no period '.' or double period '..')
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

## The main idea of this solution is to use a stack. How you decide to process the input string is a personal choice.

Your mind is telling you to split the path according to **"/"**. So, what are you waiting for? Split it!
Now the arrays you found. This array will contain paths. Some of them are simple "xyz". Some are **"."** . Some are **".."** and some are empty **""**. So, based on these elements we will insert the values in an arraylist.
- If we encounter ".." we pop the last element from the arraylist.
- If we encounter ".", we do nothing.
- In other cases, we insert in the arraylist.

# Complexity
- Time Complexity: $$O(N)$$ if there are $$N$$ characters in the `path` variable. First, we spend $$O(N)$$ trying to split the input path into components and then we process each component one by one which is again an $$O(N)$$ operation.

- Space Complexity: $$O(N)$$. Actually, it's $$2N$$ because we have the array that contains the split components and then we have the arraylist stack.

