# Approach
We can iterate over the given string and store the string between two `'/'` inside a dequeue. This stored string can be one of the 3 possible nature.

    1) It can be a normal file or folder name.
       In this can we will push it at the back of our dequeue. 
    2) It can be a "."
       In this can we will just ignore it.
    3) It can be ".."
       In this can we will pop the latest element from the back of our dequeue if it is not empty.


If after `'/'` we encounter another `'/'` we can ignore it. 

Then, after the iteration of whole string is complete, we will run a while loop till the `dequeue` is not empty to store the string present at the front of our `dequeue` to our answer and then pop that front string from our `dequeue`.
After each addition of string we will seperate the next one by adding `'/'`

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(n)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string simplifyPath(string path) {
        deque<string> s;
        int i = 0;

        while(i<path.size())
        {
            if(path[i] == '/')i++;
            else
            {
                string str = "";
                while(i<path.size() && path[i] != '/')
                {
                    str += path[i];i++;
                }
                if(str == "..")
                {
                    if(!s.empty())s.pop_back();
                }
                else if(str != ".") s.push_back(str);
            }
        }

        string ans = "/";
        while(!s.empty())
        {
            ans += s.front();
            ans += '/';
            s.pop_front();
        }
        if(ans.size()>1)
            ans.pop_back();

        return ans;
    }
};
```

