**The Entire idea is**
* We have the path
* We can split based on / slashes
* /a//b/../c/d/ -> a, b, .. , c, d = > We get the directories
* Then we need to do only ONE THING
* Put things onto stack. 
* we need to go back that is POP when we see ..
* So at last we have the PATH IN STACK.
* When we POP And CONTRUCT THE ANS. We need to do in reverse manner.
* PATH = / DIRECTORY + OLD PATH

HOW WE SPLIT?
* We could have used string stream or any other.
* But we did manually with sliding window.
* i always points to start of string and j points to the end.
* whenever u see '/' its time to enter the directory. Then move to next non slash place.

```
//TIME : O(N)
//SPACE: O(N)

class Solution {
public:
    string simplifyPath(string path) {
        vector<string> arr;
        int N = path.size();
        int i = 1;
        int j = 1;
        while(j < N){
            if(path[j] == '/'){
                arr.push_back(path.substr(i,j-i));
                //now point j to a non /
                while(path[j]=='/'){
                    j++;
                }
                i = j;
            }
            //else its not / 
            j++;
        }

        if(i<N){
            //Edge case = when there is no last back slash
            arr.push_back(path.substr(i,j-i));
        }

        stack<string> stk;

        for(auto s : arr){
            if(stk.size()>0 && s=="..") stk.pop(); // as we move one step back in directory
            else if(s != "" && s!= "." && s!="..") stk.push(s);
        }

        //edge case = when "" path is given
        if(stk.empty()) return "/";

        //PATH FORMATION
        string res="";
        while(!stk.empty()){

            res = '/' + stk.top() + res;
            stk.pop();
        }

        return res;
    }
};
```

